description.text:
This is my ultimate Kossel Mini spool guide and protection system. The design is not hermetically sealed but it protects your filament against dust, moisture and sunlight. It is able to carry 1kg spools.

I split it into 8pcs to reduce required printing radius and height to 130mm. It includes a part to see spool moving and how much filament is left (spool_window_corner.stl). A flat transparent plastic windows close the gap. Another part (spool_motor_corner.stl) is used to mount the system close to the bowden extruder.

The assembly can be fixed with M3 screws and nuts or glued together. I recommend to seal it with acrylic silicone. The (spool_bearing.stl) uses M5 screws to fix the bearing.

(Update 23.07.2017)
To enhance the bottom part i have designed a new part (spool_filament.stl) to have smooth intersection to the extruder. I also improve the (fila_cover.stl) to close gaps and to fit with the new bottom part.

(Update 30.07.2017)
(spool_support_closedv1.stl, spool_support_closedv2.stl) close open gaps in the overall "ring" assembly. All remaining (spool_support.stl) parts (developed for temporary use) will be replaced.

(Update 02.08.2017)
See updated pictures and also (floor_.stl). This is designed to close the bottom.

(Update 04.08.2017)
This Thing is NOT ANYMORE Work-In-Progress It works!!! :)

Possible Trap:
My Part (spool_filament_corner.stl) is designed as 43° (instead of ideal 45°) to compensate first layers "extension" of all 7 others. If you have a perfect printer please leave a comment and i will create the 45° version for you especially.

This was an attempt to build a chain that does not require supports. The links are built at a 45 degree angle so that most printers can print them without supports. I did find it fairly difficult to print. There are 24 links in the chain and during most of the print there are 48 separate pieces being printed. It is very easy for one of them to break loose.
I do not recommend scaling it down very much. It needs as much surface area as possible to adhere to the build surface.

I am open to suggestions on how to improve it. I was thinking of adding extra pieces to the base to make them stick better, but I thought that it might make it look worse.

title: Printrbot Simple 40mm Fan Mount with 360 Degrees Duct

description.text:
This is a 40mm fan holder with a duct that wraps around the extruder to blow down on the extruded filament and the extruded part from 3 slots located 120 degrees apart around the extruder nozzle.  
So far I've printed up to 1.5 hours without any noticeable heat problem.  
My print had a few breaches in the hull which were sealed with super glue.

VITAMINS: 6 20mm M3 screws TOOLS: Printrbot Simple
M3 HSS twist drill threaded bit Exact Thread
2,5 mm Allen wrench OPTIONAL TOOLS: 3mm Twist Drill Bit
Rotary Tool
Round Needle File INSTRUCTIONS: Printed on my Simple using 0.20 mm layer height, 3 perimeter layers (probably more than necessary and 33% hexagonal infill which gave me a weight of roughly 15 grams. Dependent on print quality you may have to drill out the two mounting holes with a 3mm twist drill bit in a rotary tool or reaming them with a needle file. Be careful not to overdo it, for stability you want an almost perfect fit. In my print they were a little large so check before reamint / drilling. Thread the four fan mount holes holes. Be careful with the one that goes into the duct, you don't want to punch a hole in the inner wall. Wait for the extruder to cool down before attempting to mount the duct! Raise the print head enough to let the duct slide around the extruder. Mount the tray extension with 2 20mm M3 screws replacing the original 16mm M3 screws.. Centre the extruder in the middle of the duct before fastening the duct securely.

Multiple chassis configurations possible.

All stl files are in the .zip download

Lots of M3 bolts (listed in assembly manual)
20mm diameter brushless inrunner motor.
Brushless ESC
13g metal gear servo
2-3s LiPo battery pack
RC radio system.

The tyres should be printed in a TPU filament. If you cannot print TPU, the buggy is compatible with standard 1/16 rear wheels and tyres. For the front, print the 1 piece wheel and tyre, then stretch a piece of bike inner tube over it.

I recommend printing all parts in PETG for better durability. I have had issues with PLA gears melting with brushless power.

Shocks:
The car is compatible with standard 1/16 scale shocks. I have also included 3D printable ones, but these only work with PETG plastic and have no damping.

Lower Body :
The lower body V2 included in the latest Erdinger Excavator zip file was a bit flimsy for my needs. All those holes at the bottom made the body bend under load, as i've put quite strong servos in it (savox 1230sg 500oz-in :D )
Also, the bottom did not seem completly flat, so i flattened the bottom too.

Stock Track Single :
The original STL file from Erdinger had 16 tracks in it, and you need 66 or 68 tracks total for the 2 sides, so you had alot of leftover in the last batch. Some people don't know how to separate those individual shells so i made this simple file that contains 1 track shoe.

Lower Big Boom V2:
(V2 Update: Bearing tolerances were too tight, fixed in V2)
Modded for bearings in the pivot holes, 4x8x3mm which is common in hobby grade R/C.
In doubt, look for Trax.xas #7019.
I use M4 bolts in both these holes.
The connector arm that goes to the servo was drilled to 4mm to fit the bolt at one end.

Track Middle Wheels :
Friction on those is pretty low, i found that simply using an M3x40mm bolt in it was enough for me (no bearings). So i filled up the inside and just left a ~3.2mm hole in it.

Arm2 Mod :
Added 2 holes for 4x8x3mm bearings at the pivot with Arm1.
Added 4 holes for 3x6x2.5mm bearings at the bucket mount and pivot arms.
In doubt, use TRA7019 and DTXC1503 for bearings.

More to come ! Small boom with bearings and if i find a way to transfer one more wire down to the tracks, i might mod a blade on it for balance and preventing sand getting in the spur gear ! :D

the troublesome stock extruder

used the original heater to save wiring the plug for the new heater

cut the connector off the original thermister and fitted it to the mk8 hotends thermister

it mounts in the same holes as the original stepper

fan is wired direcly to 12V

I will repurpose the original fan as a cooler

this mod requires the repetier reflash

extruder direction needs inverting in the configuration file (same configuration.h used when
reflashing)

no extra screws needed , enough leftover from the stock extruder

filament sensor disabled and original pcb retained fro the existing connectors

The hotend will need rotating to a position that does not clash with the plastic x carrier

the nozzle does end up off centre but its a small sacrifice for an easy upgrade to mk8

this is the setting to reverse the extruder in the configuration.h file

i have read that the wires on the stepper can be swapped around for the same effect

mine is a 1.0A so i changed to true

if DAVINCI==1 || DAVINCI==4
define EXT0_INVERSE true

description.text: ​This model of the Hard Drive Enclosure series was designed with the idea of being more space and material(s) efficient. The model (both top and base) require only 32 grams of material to print with 100% infill. At a print height of .1mm, it'll take about 7-8 hours to print both pieces depending on other quality settings. The design will require four M3 screws to mount the hard drive and they need a thread length of greater than 3mm in order to catch the threads of the hard drive itself. The opening exposes the entire SATA connection bracket, which should allow compatibility with many SATA to USB cables. There is also a .5mm gap between the PCB of the hard drive and the base, which should help prevent drive damaging if dropped and accidental electrostatic discharge. Post Processing - file any stringing from the mounting pegs in the base, ensure the enclosure fits together well, and overscrew your M3 screws through the enclosure holes before mounting your drive. Failure to do this could result in cross-threading with the threading of the hard drive itself. Due to design issues, 9.5, 12.5, and 15mm hard drive compatibility was not included with this iteration. Expect compatibility with the V6 design!

description.text:
I recently replaced an ageing and outdated Jenn-Air Microwave/Oven Combo with a modern set. Unfortunately the replacement combo was 3 inches shorter than the original units.

The attached parts were joined together provide a 27x3 inch closeout that I placed over the area left void. The assembly is attached to the area below the new units using double sided tape and M3 wood screws.

Printer:

Prusa i3 MK2S

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.20mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Use either ABS, PTEG, or equivalent high temperature filament. The oven vent is just above where the closeout Trim is mounted. Temperature can be as high as 50 degrees C in this area.

Asssembly
  • Assemble the three trim pieces with Hot Glue and double sided tape,
  • Apply one side of two sided tape on the back size full length,
  • Test fit the assembly into the desired area to insure proper alignment can be achieved,
  • Remove cover from the two sided tape and install trim piece,
  • Permanently mount trim using 4 M3 wood screws in the holes provided.

Note:
For best results install a wood filler piece across any gap below the oven. This provides backing for the screws and stability for the trim.

BOM
  • 4 ea Steel Rolling Thread Screw:
    https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00GDYDS9W
  • 3M Double Sided Tape:
    https://www.lowes.com/pd/Scotch-0-75-in-W-Two-Sided-Tape/3027105
  • PTEG Filament:
    http://www.microcenter.com/product/455111/175mm_Black_PETG_3D_Printer_Filament_-_1kg_Spool_(22_lbs)
    https://www.amazon.com/Inland-1-75mm-Black-Printer-Filament/dp/B01IIPAGY8

Design

The Trim piece is made in 3 parts due to the limitation of physical print bed size. The overall length for my application was 27 inches and I divided the three pieces equally (9" each) plus 10mm overlap to aid alignment and mounting of the final assembly.

The three pieces were affixed to each other using a thin layer of hot glue. To slow the hot glue cooling process I heated the overlap areas with a heat gun just before applying the glue and then clamped the join tightly for 5 minutes. This produced a solid joint and essentially one complete trim piece.

Note:
I tried to super glue and later Testors plastic glue but found, in each case, the bond was not very strong and the pieces broke apart during mounting.

I created a "Grill" effect by removing 54 oval shapes evenly spaced in each piece. The areas are 0.5mm deep. The Trim pieces are printed face down. Using Simplify 3D, I caused the layer above the cutouts to bridge the short way across each hole. This created an effect that resembles a screen behind a grill face. Printing face down also provides the best finish for the parts.

Note:
Make sure your print bed is smooth. Any imperfections in the bed will be reflected in the finished parts.

Finally (and Optionally) paint the assembly with spray can or air brush with paint made for plastics. This will hide and minor imperfections and make the result look as if it were supplied with the appliance.

description.text:
I just wanted to create a mini quad for beginners, the kind that can take a little of beating, without smashing to pieces.
The 1st thing that came in to my mind, was the Tiny Whoop and the Inductrix, so I decide on a ducted fan design.
I printed it all in ABS and it took almost a week to non-stop printing, considering the failed printings. My printbed is 20x20cm, so i had to split the design in several parts.
The model it only takes 4" Propellers.
It's not, by any means, a "Racer" quad, but is pretty cool to fly and is almost indestructible.

You need to print:
4 Segments, 4 wedges, 1 upper plate and 1 lower plate and 1 landing gear.

I will add more updates if I will modify the design.
The camera support is a remixed design that i found here on thingiverse, but i cant remember which one. If someone will claim the original design i will add the remix tag.

Printer:

Printrite

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0,2

Infill:

40%

Notes:

You need support only on the segments.
I printed mine in Abs:
Hobbyking ABS White 1,75mm at 250° and 110° on the bed, with a 6mm brim outside.

The other parts are:
Esun ABS Puple 1,75mm at 260° and 110 on the bed, no brim (I use buildtak)
Hobbyking ABS Solid Red 1,75mm at 250° and 110° on the bed. (no Brim as well)

Make sure that all the parts are flat, with no distortion.
Using a leveled flat surface, glue the 4 segments using thin CA glue, it will bond the parts very well, since it lightly melt the Abs.
Glue the top plate and the bottom plate with good quality 30 min epoxy.
I use a brand that is made here in Italy and is a professional and certified product and is loaded with aluminium powder, but you can use other stuff, just make sure that is not some crappy glue from the dollar store or from the bargains at hobbyking :-)
I suggest to glue the plates under some pressure, just to make sure that all is flat.
Glue the wedges as you can see in the pictures using Thin CA glue.
When all the glues are cured, make a 10mm hole in the center, in order to let the servo wire and the power wire from the pdb to reach your flight controller.
Mount your pdb on the bottom:
Just use any pdb of your choice, but must be the standard 30mm hole distance.
After you wired all the motors, mount the landing gear.
Use the motors you like more and the esc of your choice.
Use a FC with the standard 30mm hole distance.

The setup in the pictures is:
Motors: Racerstar BR1806 2280kv
Esc: DYS BL16A
Pdb: MATEK PDB-XT60
FC: Naze32 10dof with N32+gps Flashed with INAV.
The maiden flight was good and i used 3x Turnigy Nanotech 3s 1300mah to test all the stuff. I have a video, but its to large to be loaded here, so i will add it if it will be uploaded on Youtube.

My motorized bike kit had a really filmsy and unreliable mechanism for holding the clutch handle in. Since there weren't any option to print on here I designed my own. The idea was first to make two halves and clamp onto the hanlebar using zipties, but this turned out too clumbsy. Instead I made a first version of the current snap on clip that worked, but didn't have the little knobs to push it back and fourth with.

If there was anything I would change it would be to refine the thickness over the model and smooth the edges. Possibly make something a bit more stylish, but I think the clip on concept works great.

This is a remix of Dousi's Anet A8 Bowden conversion. I found that the Hotend Holder needed tweaking as my Divaks E3d V6 seems too short so the Fan duct was lower than the nozzle.

I have added slots so the part fan can be moved up and down meaning any fan duct can potentially be used on this mount. I also did the same for the Tronxy Sensor as I was not comfortable with a fixed point.

All remixed in 3DS Max and ran through Netfabb to double check for any errors

Hotend_Holder
So after printing the Hotend Holder, I noticed that the X-Carriage no longer fitted as I made it too thick on one part. Also the sensor mount needed extending as the sensor was above the fan duct so wouldn't lower down to its tolerance.

X-Carriage
I remodeled the X-Carriage as I didn't want the name attached and also added cable covers on the sides with hinges to keep the sensor, hotend and fan cables tidy. Not printed this remodel yet so not 100% if the hinges will work properly, if unsure just print Dousi's as it will still fit all these parts

Fan_Duct
The Original Fan duct was just too small for my heating block and .4 nozzle so I have modeled a Square fan duct that will fit around the Heating block. With this design and the slots on the Hotend Holder you can easily position this up and down to find the perfect height to cool your parts

title: Fidget Spinner Cap Press Out Tool

description.text:
This is a remix of 2ROBOTGUY's super awesome bearing pressout tool, which I use frequently to remove bearings from spinners without hurting either.

My problem is that sometimes when making or repairing spinners, the cap breaks inside the 608ZZ bearing. As I often have the caps glued in the bearings, they can be a real hassle to remove once broken off inside.

This tool allows you to hold the bearing captive and press the cap out. The lower bore in the cup has a 20mm diameter, so this is the max cap diameter this tool supports, but you can always scale if needed (but keep in mind your 608ZZ bearing has a 22mm O.D.)

The parts in the pictures were printed with ABS at 50% infill and 1.5mm walls (fairly stout). I use a vise (pictured) for doing the pressing, which minimizes damage to the tooling, bearings, and caps (if they aren't already broken). If you plan to use a hammer or mallet, you may need to adjust print stoutness accordingly.

Hope some of you out there find this as useful as I will, and and as useful as I've found 2ROBOTGUY's original tool. Cheers!

title: Hictop Frame Reinforcement - Stabilize frame and reduces wobble and vibrations

description.text:
Here's my full design and assembly of Z-Axis Stabiliser.

IMPORTANT INFO IT REDUCES PRINTING HEIGHT BY 1 CM

An acrylic frame of a Hictop 3DP-18 is really wobbly and vibrates a lot which causes huge echoes and ghosting on my prints(especially on corners or around circles, looks terrible).

I have decided to redesign Z-Axis top brackets(one that holds leadscrew and rod) and attach a mount for an M8 bar that connects to the front bracket of Y-Axis.

Effects seem to be promising(I am currently printing right side brackets) all lines are straight(before corners were rounded and misplaced).

Bill of materials:
-2 x 1000mm M8 threaded rods or 2 x 400mm M8 threaded rods and 2 x 600mm M8 threaded rods
-16 x M8 standard nuts
-6 x M8 Nyloc nuts
-4 x at least 25mm M5 bolts, 4 x nuts, 4 x washers
-4 x M4 bolts, nuts and washers - if using anchored bottom rod holder

Top brackets that are holding rods are also stopping Z-Axis rod from being pushed up.

I am still working on it so there might be little changes in future. I can already see that I might need to add one more hole in Z-Axis brackets and top rod holders to make sure it does not bend that much.

If you like my design make sure you let me know in comments as I'd love to know what people think about it!

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3mm

Infill:

33%

Notes:

All parts print without supports, rafts/brim can be added while printing Z-Axis brackets as they're quite big.

Preparation

  1. Check if you have the right model of Hictop Printer which is 3DP-18 - acrylic frame with display in the middle, the top part of the frame.

  2. Prepare all the parts and make sure you have necessary tools(wrenches/spanners, Allen keys, cordless drill, coffee and good mood).

  3. Cut M8 threaded rods to size - you need:
    • 2 x 400mm M8 bar (for front bracket)
    • 2 x 600mm M8 bar(to join Z-Axis bracket with Y-Axis bracket)
Assembly of Y-Axis brackets

  1. Undo screws in front of Y-Axis bracket and take it off.

  2. Slide in Left Y-Axis and Right Y-Axis brackets on the stock part.

  3. Mount stock bracket with upgraded brackets using stock screws as in the second photo.

  4. At this step, you can tension your belt again and make sure that frame is tightly secured with screws in the back and in the middle.

  5. Insert 400mm M8 brackets in 2 slots of Y-Axis printed brackets - it takes a while as holes are exactly 8mm to ensure that bars don't wobble - I used a cordless drill to screw them in(just put them inside a chunk secure it and have some fun :D). Don't worry about lengths now, just make sure that they sit inside both brackets. Make sure you put 2 nuts on each bar in between Left and right Y-axis brackets while inserting it.
Assembly of Z-Axis brackets

  1. Remove stock brackets from the top of Z-Axis - don't throw them away, you might need them one day.

  2. Put the printed brackets in the place of old ones and secure them with stock bolts and nuts - you can add some washers to spread pressure on the wider area.

  3. Once you are done attach Left top rod holder and Right top rod holder - you need M5 bolts here, again holes are exact size so they will be tight. I couldn't find any M5 nuts at home so temporarily I used M4 nuts and they do the job as well - just need to be really tight. You can add some washers to lower pressure.
Joining Z-Axis with Y-Axis

  1. At this point, you are ready to insert the 600mm M8 threaded rod in the slot. Again it is really long and the hole is tight so it will be easier and faster with a cordless drill. Screw it in until the other end is approx 30-40mm above tabletop level.

  2. Position bottom rod holder(or anchored bottom rod holder if you're willing to attach the frame to table top with M4 screws) below the overhanging rod.

OPTIONAL STEP - add anchors between y-axis brackets and bottom rod holders. It has two 4mm holes to put screws and attach it to the table - it will prevent rods from bending.

  1. Start screwing in the 400mm rod that is attached to front of Y-axis. Make sure that you put a nut before securing bottom rod holder.

  2. Once done repeat process on the other side. You have to screw in the rod far enough to the side of installed bottom rod holder so the other one can fit and then move it back to the middle so both rod holders can be attached in the right position.

  3. Put 2 nuts on each 600mm rod before connecting them to bottom rod holder.

  4. Connect 600mm rods to bottom rod holders and move one nut to each end of the bar(you can use Nylocs to make sure they stay in place).

  5. Adjust and tighten nuts so they will be pushing Y-Axis and Z-Axis away from each other(not too much tho, needs a bit of trying).

  6. Once happy with the calibration secure ends with nuts. I would personally use Nylocs on the bottom of the bracket and normal nuts for tweaking the tension on the top.
Fusion 360, lots of coffee, cigarettes and failed attempts :)

Change log

23/07/2017

  • Added anchored bottom rod holder
  • Fixed Z-Axis brackets as design was too tight on rods preventing printer from going higher than 100 mm

title: Bicycle Eyelet Stub for Light/Accessory Mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Some bike forks/racks have an M5 threaded eyelet available for various purposes. One popular use for these is to mount a light or accessory, especially if you need it to be forward of cargo. These simple cylinders are usually sold separately. Examples include the Origin8 Eyelet Stub and the Gino light mount. I wanted something cheaper, shorter, and with edges that would prevent the light from falling off.

Standard 26mm clamp diameter. 20mm of space to clamp your stuff (40mm for the extra long version). The actual clamping surface is recessed so that the raised edges keep the light from being pulled off the sides. Overall the part is about 34mm long, the clamping surface starts about 10mm from the surface you attach to.

For attaching it, you will need an M5 bolt and a washer, which are inserted through the large hole end. I found a 20mm long M5 bolt (.8 pitch) and a 15mm M5 fender washer to work perfectly, allowing about 8mm of thread to go into the eyelet on the basket. Pictures are included for detail; I paid about a dollar for the nice stuff. Of course, this assumes you are attaching this to a standard M5 eyelet - but if you aren't, this part probably isn't going to work.

I use this on my Portland Design Works Takeout Basket. I think it turned out perfectly; it's the right offset, the conical part matches up perfectly to the eyelet on the frame, and my brifters do not come near the light. I included an "extra long" version if you want more offset or want to clamp wider accessories, but have not tried it.

MP Select Mini 3D Printer V2

Yes

Yes

25%

Notes:

This was my first print on my first personal 3D printer, so the quality was okay. I used PLA because it's all I have right now. ABS is probably more appropriate, honestly.

Some things I would do differently next time:

  • Concentric top/bottom layer, just for looks.
  • Supports maybe, because if printed with the large circle down (like I would suggest) the overhang inside will be messy (but mine still worked). Perhaps printing with the small circular end down would be better, but that seemed unstable.
  • I printed a brim, not a raft, and it was really hard to separate, I ended up just sanding it off, that's why the finish is so bad in the pictures. I'm not sure it needs a raft at all.
  • I did a wall thickness of only .8mm, but an extra hour or two of printing to get this sturdier would probably serve me better long-term. The light isn't heavy, but this is outdoor equipment and might get banged around on public bike locks or something.

I sanded the bottom.

Remember to add grease to the bolt before attaching. I tried not to get any on the print because I'm not sure how it would react with PLA.

Design was centered around my specific light and the PDW basket, but this should be pretty universal. The normal version has 20mm wide mount area, the extra long is 40mm wide. I have not tried the extra long version.

title: Renkforce RF100 Y-Axis damage prevention clip plug & play

description.text:
Earlier or later the RF100 3D printer starts making a clicking noise like pressing a micro switch. But the printer still works fine. The source of the tone is hard to find.

One of my two printers had this problem, too. So I've searched many hours in the internet and made several tests myself.

The problem seems to be the belt between the y-axis and the motor (photo). Originally it is set very strong. So first I reduced this a bit, but the click sounds still existed. So I needed to disassemble the printer until I could remove the bearings at the ends of the y-axis. To repair them, simple bath them in oil for about 10 minutes. That worked for me.

Now I tried to find a solition that prevents the printer of bending the axis. First I tried to make a housing for a seperate bearing which is screwed at the top of the printer. For that it was needed to disassemble the printer and drill at least two holes into the printer housing. If it will not fit 100%ly, disassemble again and again. So this was not a good solution.

So I wanted to get a quick to install solution without loosing the guarantee.

I experimented with many clips as this. This one contains a half linear, fully printable bearing. It is plug and play. Just clip it on the axis next to the motor. That's it. It is recommend to adjust the motor to an exact 90 degree position. Use my Y-axis calibration tool for that. If not already done, print a belt tension measuring tool like mine to check the belt tension. It should have the same tension like the belts on the X-axis to be fine.

Y-axis calibration tool: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2437878
Belt tension measuring tool: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2437913

Please look at the pictures for more information and examples.

title: Low profile Titan Aero mount for P3Steel + BLtouch + radial fan mount (Updated 8-6-17)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
After coming up short in my quest to find the extruder carriage with all the features I was looking for I finally decided to design my own. This design is still a work in progress and I will be adding features as I go. Below I have a list of features, their current status in the design, and a description.

If you have any features or ideas you would like me to investigate and possibly implement, please comment! I love to hear people's feedback!

You can view more detail about this project on my personal blog - https://camdenkrupala.com/2017/07/27/building-a-better-3d-printer-carriage-adventures-in-modeling-magnets-and-auto-leveling/

Features:

  • Low Profile Design: (ADDED) I want to maximize the z height by offsetting the titan mounting fin.
  • Aluminum cased Igus Drylin Linear Bearing Mount: (ADDED) I picked these because they are interchangeable with the LM8UU bearings. Zip-tie mounting is quick and effective, and makes swapping, and thus prototyping and testing, very easy.
  • BL Touch Mount: (ADDED) Looking at mounting off the Aero aluminum fin block in line with the extruder nozzle. Investigating if this can be done without a substantial blocking of the fan.
  • Cable Connector Mount: (TESTING) A custom PCB with a 16 pin Molex Microfit connector to consolidate all the cabling. 2 pin for radial cooling fan for easy removal.
  • Radial Fan Mount: (ADDED) Looking into a way to magnetically couple the fan to the carriage for easy alignment and removal when changing nozzles.

Update 1 - Version 0.1 (7/23/2017)

Initial upload of files and addition of purpose, features, and descriptions. Carriage thus far is a very early rough stage design and has not yet been printed.

Update 2 - Version 0.2 (7/24/2017)

Added brackets for the BL touch and mounting points on the back for belt tensioning. Doing the first test print of the carriage to verify initial fit of parts before moving forward in the design process. Experimenting with angled fan placement below the stepper motor.

Update 3 (8/6/2017)

I've been messing around with a couple different configurations to figure out how best assemble/position all the parts. The newest iteration includes holes for the magnets I will be using for the fan. Additionally, I'm experimenting with different board layout designs for the connector. You will see one in the new screenshot secured to the top. Once I find one that I like, I'll make a cover to hide all the wire connections. and mounts.

No more files uploaded yet. I'm going to wait till I get to a more polished usable point till I upload any others.

description.text:
Let me open with a thank you to WinterHawk904 for his great Destiny knife model.

These are handle scales that would go on the sides of the handle to fill out the grip and protect the hand from kinetic shock and kinetic transfer down the steel of the blade and full length tang. They're used a lot in knives of today, and seeing as how the knife hasn't changed terribly much in function over all of recorded history, I set out to make some handle scales for this far future knife because it needed them (550 cord only goes so far!)

As an aside, I also made these handle scales because I split my knife into two pieces for printing...in about the middle of the handle (using Autodesk MeshMixer). This is about the right size for a 300x300 build plate. As noted by some other makers the cross section of the blade is too small (even for this HUGE knife) to just glue the ends together and be done with it.

Without there being much material to play with in the knife's cross section (to create more complex joints) I opted for an outside approach to increase the gluing surface area...which meant handle scales. I tried to keep them consistent with the look, lines, and 'appointment' of the Hunter knife and I think I have!

Make sure you line up the front (lower) part of the handle scales with the natural line of the blade bevel - the rest should fall into place well.

Last but not least - I'm totally new to the world of 3D printing and 3D design. This is my first project to 'give back' to the community writ large for some really helpful, friendly people that have made 3D printing accessible and enjoyable! Thanks everyone!

description.text:
This is a modified carriage for the ANET A6 to house the E3D V6 hotend using a bowden extruder. The carriage was designed to print easily with hardly any supports needed, and only requires a few screws for assembly. It was created in TinkerCad by scratch by combining attributes from my two favorite carriages for the A6; this carriage features a clip design for the hotend for easy removal, a larger fan for the cooling, and is super light weight.

This was a super easy print, that only requires a somewhat accurate printer and patience. This currently does not support the autolevel sensor. Highly recommend PETG.
